---
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import ProfilePhoto from '../assets/seungwon Kim profile photo.jpg';
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="About"
	description="Seungwon Kim — a model-based systems engineering consultant working across automotive, electronics, and defense, and exploring where MBSE meets AI."
	pubDate={new Date('June 14 2026')}
>
	<div class="profile">
		<Image src={ProfilePhoto} alt="Seungwon Kim" width={360} height={360} />
		<p class="name">Seungwon Kim</p>
	</div>

	<p>
		I work on complex systems — defining them as models, and helping the teams who build them put
		those models to use. For more than six years at Dassault Systèmes, I have worked as a Model-Based
		Systems Engineering (MBSE) consultant, supporting customers across the automotive, electronics,
		and defense industries. I model systems in SysML with CATIA Magic, and connect that work to the
		3DEXPERIENCE platform — designing architectures that link requirements, design, and verification
		into a single traceable structure.
	</p>

	<p>
		The work has two sides, and I try to keep them inseparable. One is engineering depth: developing
		hardware and software architectures from the system level down to components, deriving
		requirements, and validating behavior through model-based simulation. The other is making that
		work land in practice. Most of what I do happens with customers in the room — building demos and
		proofs of concept to test their requirements, resolving technical issues, and running training
		and workshops. On a software-defined vehicle project, the integrated development approach I
		proposed was later carried into a formal project RFP; while supporting an aerospace manufacturer,
		I worked through more than thirty technical issues and helped turn that feedback into further
		adoption. A good method matters only if it survives contact with a real product.
	</p>

	<p>
		I believe the essence of systems engineering is turning complexity into a structure people can
		actually work with. And the way we handle that complexity is now changing quickly with AI — both
		how models are built and how they are explained and delivered to the people who rely on them.
		That is the question I keep returning to: how AI can be brought into MBSE, and how the role of a
		systems engineer changes in an AI-driven era.
	</p>

	<p>
		I also care about sharing what I learn. I post about systems engineering on YouTube, and this
		blog began for the same reason — a place to record the problems I work on and how I solve them,
		and to share them with others working through similar questions.
	</p>

	<p>
		The harder the engineering problem, the more I trust a systematic, model-based approach. This is
		where I write that thinking down.
	</p>

	<section class="cv">
		<h2>Experience</h2>
		<div class="cv-head">
			<span class="org">Dassault Systèmes</span>
			<span class="period">Feb 2020 – Present</span>
		</div>
		<p class="cv-sub">
			<strong>MBSE Industry Process Consultant</strong> · Sep 2021 – Present<br />
			MBSE consulting and proofs of concept for automotive, electronics, and defense customers —
			including Hyundai Motor, LG Electronics, Korea Aerospace Industries (KAI), and Hyundai Rotem.
			SysML-based system architecture, model-based simulation, and training.
		</p>
		<p class="cv-sub">
			<strong>ENOVIA Industry Process Consultant</strong> · Feb 2020 – Aug 2021<br />
			PLM/PDM solution proposals and PoC projects based on customer requirements, including BOM and
			change-management process analysis.
		</p>

		<h2>Education</h2>
		<p class="cv-sub">
			<strong>M.S. in Systems Engineering</strong> · Ajou University · 2024–2026
		</p>
		<p class="cv-sub">
			<strong>B.S. in Naval Architecture &amp; Ocean Engineering</strong> · Inha University · 2012–2019
		</p>
	</section>
</Layout>

<style>
	.profile {
		text-align: center;
		margin-bottom: 2.5em;
	}
	.profile img {
		width: 180px;
		height: 180px;
		border-radius: 50%;
		object-fit: cover;
		box-shadow: var(--box-shadow);
	}
	.profile .name {
		margin-top: 0.8em;
		margin-bottom: 0;
		font-weight: 600;
		color: rgb(var(--black));
	}
	.cv {
		margin-top: 3em;
		border-top: 1px solid rgb(var(--gray-light));
		padding-top: 1.5em;
	}
	.cv h2 {
		font-size: 1.5rem;
		margin-top: 1.5em;
		margin-bottom: 0.6em;
	}
	.cv h2:first-child {
		margin-top: 0;
	}
	.cv-head {
		display: flex;
		justify-content: space-between;
		align-items: baseline;
		gap: 1rem;
	}
	.cv-head .org {
		font-weight: 700;
		font-size: 1.15rem;
		color: rgb(var(--black));
	}
	.cv-head .period {
		color: rgb(var(--gray));
		font-size: 0.9rem;
		white-space: nowrap;
	}
	.cv-sub {
		margin: 0.6em 0 1.2em 0;
		color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
		font-size: 0.98rem;
		line-height: 1.6;
	}
	.cv-sub strong {
		color: rgb(var(--black));
	}
	@media (max-width: 720px) {
		.cv-head {
			flex-direction: column;
			gap: 0.2rem;
		}
	}
</style>
